    <p>Chrome design is utilitarian and simple. Yet, I didn’t find the file download flow on Chrome very practical. It has a lot of unnecessary steps that could be minimized. And in particular, I didn't like the download bar which took up valuable horizontal screen real estate at the bottom of the screen.</p>

    <div class="project-detail-divider"></div>

    <h2>The Problem</h2>

    <div class="image-container">
        <img src="/static/img/projects/chromedl/screenshot01.png" alt="chrome current download ui" class="project-image image-width-80">
        <figcaption>Is that download bar needed when there is only one downloaded item?</figcaption>
    </div>

    <p>Every download starts with a giant, blue arrow on the left. It slides down slowly to indicate your downloaded file is on the far left side of the download bar.  This download bar comes up every time a file is downloaded on Chrome. Once it comes up, it stays on unless it’s manually closed. This is what bothered me the most. Because it requires a specific action, it interrupts my experience on Chrome. Nonetheless, I find the download bar intrusive; the fact that it stays on the browser makes me wonder if Chrome is expecting me to download more files.</p>

    <div class="image-container">
        <img src="/static/img/projects/chromedl/screenshot02.png" alt="Ugly downloads page" class="project-image image-width-80 project-image-in-text">
    </div>

    <p>Another feature on the download bar that I find disappointing is lack of emphasis on download history. This history page is an archive with all the downloaded files and incidents, showing the URL and the downloaded file. Hence, even if you empty out your download folder, you can search and retrieve your files from here.</p>

    <div class="project-detail-divider"></div>

    <h2>Sketches</h2>

    <div class="image-container">
        <img src="/static/img/projects/chromedl/chromedlsketches.png" alt="Sketches for the chrome download redesign" class="project-image image-width-100">
