    <h2>Final Mockup</h2>

    <div class="image-container">
        <img src="/static/img/projects/chromedl/full.png" alt="Final mockup for chrome download redesign" class="project-image image-width-100">
    </div>

    <p>So… what does the download bar really show? It has recently downloaded files, quick access to download history, and the status of current download. Are these all necessary? Downloading progress is important but they don’t need to be present at all times. Debating and measuring on priority of these factors helped me clear unnecessary items, ultimately leading me to remove the bar and replace with a collapsible menu bar. My proposal places a menu icon for downloads next to the Settings icon on the upper right side of the browser. This way, recently downloaded files can be accessed quickly and the download status can be integrated seamlessly.</p>

    <p>When a file is downloaded, a quick preview will come up on the upper right side. The download can be paused, canceled or resumed. Once download is finished, it will have two options available: Open or Open in Finder. Clicking on the Downloads icon in the menu bar will drop down recently downloaded files. Downloads history can also be accessed from the drop down menu.</p>

